Using distinct() with Objects

distinct() uses the equals() and hashCode() methods to determine whether two objects are duplicates.

For primitive wrapper classes like Integer and String, it works automatically.

For custom classes such as Employee, if you want to remove duplicate Employee objects directly, you should override equals() and hashCode().

Interview Question

Q. Does distinct() modify the original collection?

Answer: No. It returns a new Stream containing unique elements. The original collection remains unchanged.

Example:

List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 10, 30);

numbers.stream()
       .distinct()
       .forEach(System.out::println);

System.out.println(numbers);

Output:

10
20
30

[10, 20, 10, 30]

The original list is not modified.
